    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Freshy, tufted perennial with shortish trailing stems emerging from a thick tap root and then curling upwards distally. Stems often pinkish and bear numerous, elongate, smooth, 3-angled leaves. Large, solitary yellow flowers born on long, erect stalks and have numerous (200-250) petals surrounding a tangle of thin stamens at the center. Fruit cone-shaped and contain 8-23 chambers.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_10166",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Stems up to about 40 cm long, flowers 50-80 mm across.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_10167",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa. Artificially introduced to California, where it is considered a minor problem plant.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Namaqualand to Eastern Cape. Separate west and east coast subspecies are recognised.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_10168",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Common on sandy flats close to the coast throughout the winter rainfall region. The large, unpleasant-smelling flowers only open in sunlight and are pollinated by bees and beetles. The plants have a strong taproot which allows them to resprout if severed near the base, or damaged by fire of trampling.&nbsp; The roots are also favoured food for pigs, hence the Afrikaans name of Varkslaai (meaning pig salad).&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_10169",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_10170",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Flowers September to November.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_10171",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Could be confused with Sour figs (<i>Carpobrotus</i> species) but those have much longer, trailing stems, shorter, fatter leaves and the flowers have thicker petals and much shorter stems.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_10172",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Manning, J (2007). Field Guide to Fynbos. Cape Town: Random House Struik. (p. 324).<br><br>Manning, J & Goldblatt, P (2000). South African Wild Flower Guide 7: West Coast. Botanical Society of South Africa (p. 104).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_10173",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
